&lt;p&gt;A long standing dependency of &lt;a href="https://neuralensemble.github.io/MotionClouds/"&gt;MotionClouds&lt;/a&gt; is MayaVi. While powerful, it is tedious to compile and may discourage new users. We are trying here to show some attempts to do the same with the &lt;a href="http://vispy.org"&gt;vispy&lt;/a&gt; library.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In &lt;a href="https://laurentperrinet.github.io/sciblog/posts/2014-10-08_moving-from-mayavi-to-matplotlib.html"&gt;another post&lt;/a&gt;, we tried to use matplotlib, but this had some limitations. Let's now try &lt;a href="http://vispy.org"&gt;vispy&lt;/a&gt;, a scientific visualisation library in python using opengl.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://laurentperrinet.github.io/sciblog/posts/2015-04-29-moving-from-mayavi-to-vispy.html"&gt;Read more…&lt;/a&gt; (25 min remaining to read)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>motionclouds</category><category>python</category><category>vispy</category><guid>https://laurentperrinet.github.io/sciblog/posts/2015-04-29-moving-from-mayavi-to-vispy.html</guid><pubDate>Wed, 29 Apr 2015 07:56:28 GMT</pubDate></item></channel></rss>